solutions.content:
#### The dummy ListNode declaration in this code is used to simplify the code when handling edge cases where the reversal of nodes needs to occur within the given linked list. Specifically, it helps in handling the cases where left is equal to 1 or where left is greater than 1.

##### 1.left is equal to 1: In this case, the dummy ListNode (tmep) allows you to insert a new node at the beginning of the linked list to handle the reversal. Without a dummy node, you would need special logic to handle the case where the reversal starts from the head of the linked list.

##### 2.left is greater than 1: In this case, the dummy ListNode is used to create a reference (prev) to the node just before the left-th node.

# Code
```

class Solution {
public:
    ListNode* reverseBetween(ListNode* head, int left, int right) {
        // Check if the input list is empty; if so, return it as is.
        if (!head) return head;

        // Create a dummy node with a value of 0 and set its next to the head.
        ListNode *temp = new ListNode(0);
        temp->next = head;

        // Initialize a 'prev' pointer to the dummy node.
        ListNode *prev = temp;

        // Move 'prev' to the node just before the 'left' index.
        for (int i = 0; i < left - 1; i++) {
            prev = prev->next;
        }

        // Initialize a 'curr' pointer to 'prev->next'.
        ListNode *curr = prev->next;

        // Reverse the portion of the list between 'left' and 'right'.
        for (int i = 0; i < right - left; i++) {
            // Store the next node after 'curr' in 'nex'.
            ListNode* nex = curr->next;

            // Update the next of 'curr' to point to the node after 'nex',
            // effectively detaching 'curr' from the list.
            curr->next = nex->next;

            // Update 'nex->next' to point to 'prev->next', effectively reversing
            // the direction of the next pointer of 'nex'.
            nex->next = prev->next;

            // Update 'prev->next' to point to 'nex', effectively linking 'nex'
            // as the new next node after 'prev'.
            prev->next = nex;
        }

        // Return the modified linked list, starting from 'temp->next'.
        return temp->next;
    }
};







```

