# Approach
So firstly return ```null``` if ```head``` doesn't exist.

- Now , since we have to reverse the list from ```left to right``` we will first traverse till our ```left``` node, this we will do with the help of our ```prev``` Node, prev would point to the node before (previous) to our left node.
- So our ```current``` node would be prev->next.
- Create a ```next``` node pointing to ```null```, this will tell us which node to process next.
- Now for ```right- left times``` , i.e for the given number of nodes starting left, we reverse the linked list.
- This is done by 
```
next = current->next;
current->next = next->next;
next->next = prev->next;
prev->next = next;
```
# Refer to the image below for first test case
![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/9402f82d-73a5-4354-9d9e-095c23734f78_1694062838.3300138.png)

# Code
```
/**
 * Definition for singly-linked list.
 * struct ListNode {
 *     int val;
 *     ListNode *next;
 *     ListNode() : val(0), next(nullptr) {}
 *     ListNode(int x) : val(x), next(nullptr) {}
 *     ListNode(int x, ListNode *next) : val(x), next(next) {}
 * };
 */
class Solution {
public:
    ListNode* reverseBetween(ListNode* head, int left, int right) {
        // Handle the edge case of an empty list
    if (!head) return nullptr;

    // Create a dummy node to handle the case when left = 1
    ListNode* dummy = new ListNode(0);
    dummy->next = head;

    // Move to the node before the sublist
    ListNode* prev = dummy;
    for (int i = 0; i < left - 1; i++) {
        prev = prev->next;
    }

    // Start reversing the sublist
    ListNode* current = prev->next;
    ListNode* next = nullptr;

    for (int i = 0; i < right - left; i++) {
        next = current->next;
        current->next = next->next;
        next->next = prev->next;
        prev->next = next;
    }

    return dummy->next;

    }
};
```

