solutions.content:
Of course we can write
```
   return n%4;
```
to solve the problem.

However, this is a good chance to use the basic idea of dynamic programming (DP). The idea is that we build the (partial) solution array as the scale of the program goes up, namely, we build res[0,1,2,...,].

Here's the code:

```
	bool canWinNim(int n) {
			//return n%4; // of course we know this one
			vector<bool> res(n,false); // allocate the vector in advance
			res[1]=res[2]=res[3]=true; // known knowledge
			for(int i=4;i<=n;i++){ // generate new knowledge while the scale goes larger
			    res[i]=(res[i-1]==false || res[i-2]==false || res[i-3]==false);
			}
			return res[n];
	}
```

