this is the final solution to this question.it's based on the conclusion:**the period of the function is :4**
```
bool canWinNim(int n){
    bool  a[] = {true, true, true, false};
    return a[(n - 1) % 4];
}
```
we can assume that the function **f(n)** indicates whether i can win the game  when there are **n** stones.(just the same as the description in question)
clearly, when **n<=3, f(n) = True**. let us focus on the condition when **n>=4**: now i have three choices to remove stone: remove 1,2 or 3 stone ,then your friend begin to remove the stone. **from the perspective of your friend: if you choose to remove 1 stone ,then his game result is :f(n-1) and your game result is !f(n-1),(you and your friend have opposite result), similarly the result of your friend are f(n-2) and f(n-3) corresponding to  when you remove 2 and 3 stones.**

then we can get the following equation:
**when n>=4, f(n) = !f(n-1) || !f(n-2) || !f(n-3)**

besed on the above equation, we can get the recursive algorithm:
```
bool canWinNim(int n){
    if(n<=3) return true;
    else return !(canWinNim3(n-1) && canWinNim3(n-2) && canWinNim3(n-3));
}
```

obviously it can't pass all test cases since the recursive process have a lot of function value to be repeating calculated.so we can use **dynamic programming(DP)** method to optimize the algorithm:
we can use an array to save the calculated function value.
```
bool canWinNim(int n) {
    if (n<=3) return true;
    bool *data = new bool [n];
    for(int i=0;i<3;i++) {
        data[i] = true;
    }
    for(int i=3;i<n;i++){
        data[i] = !data[i-1] || !data[i-2] || !data[i-3];

    }
    return data[n-1];
}
```
but this algorithm can't pass the 50th test case since exceeding time limit.
**so by the observation, we can found the function has the period :4**, it's result like:1,1,1,0, 1,1,1,0,...,111,0.
so i use basic mathematical proof method : **mathematical induction** to prove the period of function  is 4.
the following image show the process:(because of editer can't use math equation ,so i writed it on another markdown editer.)
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/ma_hongying/image_1587291168.png)

now the final version of algorithm is produced:
```
bool canWinNim(int n){
    bool  a[] = {true, true, true, false};
    return a[(n - 1) % 4];
}
