solutions.content:
I was tempted for a moment to use DP to solve this and, while I am sure it would work, I quickly realised it was an overkill in this case:
* if I have less than `4` stones, I automatically win by definition, since I can grab all of the in one go;
* if I have `4`, I automatically lose, since no matter how many I take, my opponent will be in the winning position described above;
* if I have `5-7` stones, I can force my opponent in the losing scenario of the previous bullet point;
* if I have `8`, my opponent will end up in the winning scenario above, no matter what;
* and so on...

Now, this means that basically we lose for every multiple of `4` we face.

We might be tempted to `return` something like `n % 4 != 0` or just `n % 4`, but that would be still doing a relatively expensive operation as dividing two numbers.

Since we want the remainder by a power of `2`, we can still do better using bitwise operators: if we do `n & 3`, we will `return` a truthy (ie: `!= 0`) value every time that the least significant bits are not `00`, that is to say we would `return` `true` every time `n` is NOT a multiple of `4`.

The code:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    bool canWinNim(int n) {
        return n & 3;
    }
};
```

