solutions.content:
**One-line solution:**
Imagine these conditions during our move:
1. 1-3 stones left -> we can directly remove them all -> win
2. 4 stones left -> after our move, there will be 1-3 stones left (the opponent will face condition 1 -> win) -> lose
3. 5 or more stones left -> there can more rounds which will lead to either condition 1 or 2
```
function canWinNim(n: number): boolean {
    return n % 4 !== 0;
};
```

**Dynamic Programming (DP) solution:**
```
function canWinNim(n: number): boolean {
    if (n < 4) return true;

    const prevWin: boolean[] = [true, true, true];

    for (let stone = 4; stone <= n; stone++) {
        const optimalRes = !prevWin[0] || !prevWin[1] || !prevWin[2];
        prevWin.shift();
        prevWin.push(optimalRes);
    }

    return prevWin[2];
};
```

