# Intution

The intution behind this is that we can **use two pointers, one for tracking the String s and another one for tracking String t.**
We will iterate for both pointers while the are not reached till end. Lets take example -> 
s = "abc", t = "ahbgdc"
i = 0,  j = 0
So iteration will look something like this ->
check if s[i] = t[j] -> true, increment i
i = 1, j = 1
check if s[i] = t[j] -> false
i = 1, j = 2
check if s[i] = t[j] -> true, increment i
i = 2, j = 3
check if s[i] = t[j] -> false
i = 2, j = 4
check if s[i] = t[j] -> false
i = 2, j = 5
check if s[i] = t[j] -> true, increment i
break;
##### Now return true if i == s.length() else false -> this means that if we reached till end we have found a substring other wise t doesn't had a substring.

# Solution
Below is the C++ Code ->
```
class Solution {
public:
    bool isSubsequence(string s, string t) {
        int i = 0, j = 0;
        while(i < s.length() && j < t.length())
        {
            if(s[i] == t[j]) i++;
            j++;
        }
        return i == s.length();
    }
};
```
