# Intuition
Basic Linear Searching with some conditions will do the trick

# Approach
- Create a new string ***str***
- Then, search linearly and see if any character in ***s string* **matches the one with ***t string's*** character.
- if it does, then ***push_back*** it to the ***str* **string
- after the loop completes, check if ***str==s***

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(n)

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    bool isSubsequence(string s, string t) {
        int strCount = 0;
        int start = 0,end = t.length();

        string str;

        while(start < end && strCount < s.length()){
            if(s[strCount] == t[start]){
                str.push_back(t[start]);
                strCount++;
            }

            start++;

        }

        if(s==str)
            return true;
        else
            return false;

    }
};
```

