# Approach
``isSubsequence`` that takes two strings, s and t, as input. The function checks whether string s is a subsequence of string t and returns true if it is, or false otherwise.

Here's an explanation of the approach used in this code:

- Initialize an integer variable j to 0. This variable will keep track of the current position in string s that we are trying to match.

- Check if string s is an empty string. If it is, return true because an empty string is considered a subsequence of any string.

- Iterate through the characters of string t using a for loop with index i.

- Inside the loop, compare the character s[j] with the character t[i].If they are equal, it means we have found a character in t that matches the current character we are looking for in s.

- If there is a match, increment the j index by 1. This moves us to the next character we need to find in s.

- Check if j has reached the length of string s (s.size()). If it has, it means we have successfully matched all characters in s to a subsequence of t, so we return true.

- If the loop completes without finding all characters in s, return false because s is not a subsequence of t.

This code effectively iterates through both strings, s and t, in a single pass and checks if s is a subsequence of t. If all characters in s are found in t in the same order, the function returns true; otherwise, it returns false.





