##### Dynamic Programming Approach
> Dp Sol is Less Optimized.

**Idea:** We can determine the `longest common subsequence` of `s` and `t` and return `true` if the size of the longest common subsequence is equal to`s.size()`, otherwise `false`.
>Time: O(N * M), Space: O(N * M)

**C++ Code:**
```
bool isSubsequence(string s, string t) {
        int n = t.size(), m = s.size();
        vector<vector<int>>dp(n+1,vector<int>(m+1, 0));

        for(int i=1;i<=n;i++){
            for(int j=1;j<=m;j++){
                if(s[j-1] == t[i-1])
                    dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1] + 1;
                else
                    dp[i][j] = max(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1]);
            }
        }
        return dp[n][m] == m;
    }
```

##### Two pointer Approach | O(N) Time Solution
> Most optimized sol for this problem.

**Idea:** Taking two index pointers, one for each of the two input strings (`s_ptr` for `s` and `t_ptr` for `t` string) and simply iterate over  `t` and `s` together. If there is a common character in both the strings, then move both `s_ptr` and `t_ptr` forward by one, else move only the `t ptr` forward.
Once the loop terminates (when either `s_ptr` has reached the end of `s` string, or the `t_ptr` has reached the end of `t` string), we check if the `s_ptr` has reached the end of the `s` string. If yes then `s` is a subsequence of `t` and we return `true`, otherwise return `false`. 
> Time: O(N), Space: O(1)

**C++ Code:**
```
 bool isSubsequence(string s, string t){
     int t_ptr = 0, s_ptr = 0;
     if(s.size()>t.size())
		 return false;
	 while(t_ptr < t.size() and s_ptr<s.size()){
		 if(t[t_ptr] == s[s_ptr]){
			 s_ptr++;
			 t_ptr++;
         }else
			 t_ptr++;
      }
     return (s_ptr == s.size());
    }
```

